The '''Military Action Against Iraq (Parliamentary Approval) Bill''' was a [[private member's bill]] introduced into the [[United Kingdom House of Commons]] by [[Tam Dalyell]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] under the [[Ten Minute Rule]]. It received its formal [[first reading]] on 26 January 1999.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmhansrd/vo990126/debtext/90126-06.htm#90126-06_spnew9 First reading] (''[[Hansard]]'', 26 January 1999, Col.145)</ref> The bill sought to transfer the power to authorise military strikes against [[Iraq]] from the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|monarch]] to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]. The [[long title]] of the bill was "A Bill to require the prior approval, by a simple majority of the House of Commons, of military action by United Kingdom forces against Iraq".<ref>[http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm199899/cmbills/035/1999035.htm Military Action Against Iraq (Parliamentary Approval) Bill] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050505112555/http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/cm199899/cmbills/035/1999035.htm |date=2005-05-05 }} (full text from [[The Stationery Office]])</ref> It was presented by Tam Dalyell and supported by [[Tony Benn]], [[Harry Cohen]], [[Jeremy Corbyn]], [[George Galloway]], [[Neil Gerrard]], [[Ian Gibson (politician)|Dr Ian Gibson]], [[John McAllion]], [[Alice Mahon]], [[Robert Marshall-Andrews]], [[Dennis Skinner]] and [[Audrey Wise]].<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmhansrd/vo990126/debtext/90126-07.htm First reading] (''[[Hansard]]'', 26 January 1999, Col.147)</ref>
The [[Bill (proposed law)|bill]] became Bill 35 in the 1998/1999 Parliamentary session, and was initially scheduled for [[second reading]] on 16 April 1999. As a bill modifying the [[monarch]]'s [[royal prerogative|prerogative powers]], [[Queen's Consent]] was required before it could be debated in Parliament. The Queen, acting upon the advice of her government{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}, refused to grant her consent for the Bill to be debated. The second reading was initially postponed from 16 April until 23 July 1999.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmhansrd/vo990416/debtext/90416-21.htm Extract] (''[[Hansard]]'', 16 April 1999, Col.521) ("Queen's consent has not been signified. Second Reading what day? ... Friday 23 July.")</ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmwib/wb990717/pub.htm Weekly Information Bulletin] (17 July 1999, giving second reading date)</ref> Due to the [[The Crown|Crown]]'s continuing refusal to signify its consent to the Bill being debated, it could not receive its second reading on 23 July 1999. In the absence of a request for a further postponement, the Bill was automatically dropped before it obtained its second reading.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmagenda/ob990723.htm Order of Business] (23 July 1999) ("Queen's Consent to be signified")</ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmhansrd/vo990723/debtext/90723-23.htm Extract] (''[[Hansard]]'', 23 July 1999, Col.1545) ("As the Queen's consent has not been obtained, this cannot be dealt with. Second Reading what day? No day named.") </ref><ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmwib/wb990729/pub.htm Weekly Information Bulletin] (29 July 1999)("''Commons: (35) 1R: 26.1.99 (Dropped)''")</ref>
When [[2003 invasion of Iraq|military action against Iraq]] was eventually organised in 2003, the government sought [[18 March 2003 Parliamentary approval for the invasion of Iraq|Parliamentary approval]] on 18 March 2003, one day before the invasion began, although no powers under the [[royal prerogative]] were thereby transferred to Parliament.
